Objective
The objective of this module is to group crops with similar soil and environmental conditions using the K-Means Clustering algorithm. This helps in identifying patterns within the agricultural dataset and improves crop recommendation analysis.

Algorithm Used
K-Means Clustering

Input Parameters
The following parameters are used for clustering:

Nitrogen (N)
Phosphorus (P)
Potassium (K)
Temperature
Humidity
pH Value
Rainfall
Methodology
Step 1: Data Collection

The crop recommendation dataset containing soil nutrients and environmental parameters is collected.

Step 2: Data Preprocessing
Check for missing values.
Handle outliers.
Standardize numerical features using StandardScaler.
Step 3: Clustering

The K-Means algorithm is applied to the dataset to divide the crops into different clusters based on their similarities.

Step 4: Cluster Assignment

Each record is assigned a cluster label and stored in the dataset.

Output

A new column named Cluster is added to the dataset.

Example:

N	P	K	Temperature	Humidity	pH	Rainfall	Crop	Cluster
90	42	43	20.8	82	6.5	202	Rice	1
Advantages
Groups similar crops together.
Improves agricultural data analysis.
Helps identify crop patterns.
Supports machine learning model development.
Tools and Technologies Used
Python
Pandas
NumPy
Scikit-Learn
Google Colab
Conclusion

K-Means Clustering successfully groups crops based on soil nutrients and environmental conditions. The generated clusters can be used for further analysis and crop recommendation model development.
